  "location": "A street food stall or bakery counter, anywhere in Hong Kong",
  "context": "This is the toolkit scene: the handful of phrases you'll reach for in almost any first encounter, whether that's a stallholder, a neighbour, or someone you've just bumped into on the street. Shadow this one first, before anything location-specific.",
  "cultural_note": "Cantonese has two words for \"thank you\" and mixing them up is the single most common beginner slip. 唔該 (m4 goi1) is for services and small favours: someone hands you something, holds a door, gives you your change. 多謝 (do1 ze6) is for gifts and genuine kindness: a present, a compliment, someone going out of their way for you. Locals notice the swap even when the sentence is otherwise perfect.",
